est file would be more appropriate. I could consider defining a Scala test that uses Java reflection, but that doesn't feel ideal either. Let me rethink this access approach.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test file restrictions**\\n\\nI don't see a strict rule against using a Java helper, but the user wants dedicated coverage in a Scala test file. I could create a Scala test that calls a Java fixture, but it seems tricky if I'm directly testing the Java helper. Perhaps I can use a test class within a specific package that instantiates the MegaMethodCache. Still, the class is runtime internal, not part of the public API. I’ll have to think about how to balance these access rules while ensuring proper coverage.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test implementation**\\n\\nThe Java test helper would instantiate `MegaMethodCache` directly, using `find(String.class)`, which calls `getMethod`. This seems to bypass the restriction against direct reflection unless we're dealing with the public API. While this isn’t exactly direct reflection, it does involve an internal class. I wonder if that would be acceptable. The user requested dynamic access, and maybe I could create a Scala test file that incorporates the Java helper without being strictly dedicated. This needs careful consideration.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Java and Scala integration**\\n\\nI’m considering how the Java helper approach compiles with javac while ignoring ScalaSignature. I might need to add a Java source file; using Gradle with the Scala plugin would help with the compilation too. Testing can be organized under `src/test/scala`, and I'm reflecting on whether I should avoid using the \\\"substring\\\" method that requires reflection metadata. \\n\\nAlso, I think using a method from `scala.Tuple2` could be a good alternative, allowing the Java helper to reference Scala properly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying Java helper reflection use**\\n\\nI’m considering if I really need to avoid direct reflection in my tests. The Java helper avoids using reflection APIs, only relying on class literals. It returns `java.lang.reflect.Method` from the library, so maybe an assertion on this is acceptable? In the Scala test, I could assert that `MegaMethodCacheInvoker.findProductArityMethodName()` equals \\\"productArity.\\\" The Java helper calls the `find` method, which seems straightforward. I just want to ensure everything is set up correctly!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_zgcNuHS1MYfFiCnryVBxFnT0|fc_0ab739bc3b3726c90169f53521faf081929e2fc54b5d9581bb", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.scala-lang/scala-library/2.11.8/src/test/scala/org_scala_lang/scala_library/ScalaRunTimeTest.scala", "limit": 120}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 630, "output": 1421, "cacheRead": 25088, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 27139, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777677581058, "responseId": "resp_0ab739bc3b3726c90169f5350d89b0819299ef1c1002fbd815"}}
